# Canon Tasks — assignable work items (automatic in wired repos)

This repo has `canon task`: a tenant-scoped task tracker for writing work for
each other to complete. When `CANON_TASKS_API_URL` (or `CANON_STATE_API_URL`) is
set, tasks are **server-authoritative** via state-api (instant sync across
machines). The on-disk NDJSON ledger is an offline cache. Everything is
**fail-open**.

## Automatic wiring (no manual steps per turn)

When this repo is wired (`canon setup` / `canon enable-repo`), Cursor hooks run
automatically:

| Hook | When | What it does |
| --- | --- | --- |
| `task-preflight.sh` | Before each user prompt | Refreshes `.canon/tasks/active-context.json`, promotes the active open task to `in_progress`, surfaces open tasks in a system message |
| `task-session.sh` | After each assistant response | Aligns active task with `tsk_*` mentions; **appends deduped `[auto]` progress notes** (batch: every mentioned `tsk_*` in the turn); extracts branch/PR/deploy hints |
| `memory-capture.sh` | After each response | Captures the turn to AWS memory with `work_item_ids` = active `task_ref` |

Opt out: `CANON_TASKS_PREFLIGHT=0`, `CANON_TASKS_SESSION_HOOK=0`, `CANON_TASKS_AUTO_NOTE=0`.
Tune note size: `CANON_TASKS_AUTO_NOTE_MIN_CHARS` (default 80), `CANON_TASKS_AUTO_NOTE_MAX_CHARS` (default 420).

Template updates propagate via **auto-rewire** when `CANON_TEMPLATE_BUNDLE_ID`
in `.canon/memory-layer.local.env` lags the installed package (run any `canon`
command in the repo, or `canon enable-repo`).

## Agent loop ("what's next?")

When the user asks what to work on next, run:

```
canon task next --json
```

Then work, attribute progress, and advance:

```
canon task update <task_ref> --status in_progress --branch <branch> --note "<what you did>"
canon task update <task_ref> --deployment <url-or-target> --note "deployed"
canon task close <task_ref> --comment "<shipped + evidence>"
canon task next --json
```

Creating work for someone else:

```
canon task create "Title" --assignee usr_x --body "..." [--priority high] [--scope company|multi-repo --repos r1,r2]
canon task assign <task_ref> usr_y [--replace]
```

## When to use it

- The user asks to "create a task", "assign", "hand off", "leave a task for
  <person>", "what tasks do I have", "what's assigned to me", or similar.
- You finish work that implies a follow-up someone else should own — **create
  the task** (do not only mention it in chat).

## Scopes

- `repo` (default) — `.canon/tasks/ledger.ndjson` (git-tracked).
- `company` — all repos for this `company_id`.
- `multi-repo` — explicit `--repos r1,r2`.

## Commands

```
canon task create "Title" [--body ...] [--scope repo|company|multi-repo]
                          [--repos r1,r2] [--assignee usr_x] [--priority high]
canon task next [--any] [--json]
canon task list [--mine] [--status open] [--all-repos] [--json]
canon task show <task_ref> [--json]
canon task update <task_ref> [--status ...] [--branch ...] [--deployment ...] [--note "..."]
canon task assign <task_ref> usr_a [usr_b ...] [--replace]
canon task comment <task_ref> "note"
canon task close <task_ref> [--cancel] [--comment "..."]
canon task sync [--scan-localwork]
canon task active --refresh   # hooks call this; pins session task context
```

## Tenant boundaries

Tasks use `company_id` + `repository_id` from `.canon/memory-layer.local.env`.
Do not move tasks across companies.
